"'''Mist Encounter'''" is a short story written by [[Timothy Zahn]] and illustrated by [[Doug Shuler]], originally published in [[Star Wars Adventure Journal 7|''Star Wars Adventure Journal'' 7]] by [[West End Games]] in August 1995. It was later printed in the paperback version of [[Outbound Flight (novel)|''Outbound Flight'']], which was published by [[Del Rey]] in January 2007, and the republishing in 2023 as part of ''[[The Essential Legends Collection]]''. It has also been made available online at [[Hyperspace: The Official Star Wars Fan Club|Hyperspace]]. An unabridged recording is included in the [[Outbound Flight (unabridged audiobook)|unabridged audiobook]].

The newer version contains some changes made presumably to fit in with events in the [[Prequel trilogy|prequels]] since the story's original printing. One such edit includes an early mention of Palpatine as "[[Supreme Chancellor/Legends|Chancellor]]" of the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Republic]] and his reorganization of the government into the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]], two details not revealed until the respective releases of [[Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace|''The Phantom Menace'']] in [[1999]] and [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|''Revenge of the Sith'']] in [[2005]].

''Mist Encounter'' was also included in Czech-language anthology ''[[Setkání v mlze]]'' in [[2009]].

==Plot summary==
[[File:MistEncounterSplash.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Imperials in battle]]
This story is about how the [[Exile (punishment)/Legends|exiled]] [[Mitth'raw'nuruodo/Legends|Mitth'raw'nuruodo]] came into [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] service.

Imperial [[Star Destroyer/Legends|Star Destroyer]] [[Strikefast/Legends|''Strikefast'']] was chasing the [[Smuggler/Legends|smuggler]] [[Booster Terrik]] into the [[Unknown Regions/Legends|Unknown Regions]]. After a blind jump trying (and failing) to escape the pursuing ''Strikefast'', Terrik discovered an inhabitable planet at the edge of Known Space. With his [[Hyperdrive/Legends|hyperdrive]] damaged from the last jump, Terrik made for the planet to hole up in a cave (shooting down two pursuing [[TIE/ln space superiority starfighter/Legends|TIE fighters]] in the process), using an "unknown energy signature" to cover his landing position from the pursuing Star Destroyer.

Meanwhile, on the ''Strikefast'', a fuming [[Captain/Legends|Captain]] [[Voss Parck/Legends|Voss Parck]] received the report about the "unknown energy signature." Hampered by the standing Navy "Unknown Alien Encounter" orders, he was forced to send down a detachment of soldiers and technicians under the command of [[Colonel/Legends|Colonel]] [[Mosh Barris/Legends|Mosh Barris]] to check it out, instead of proceeding with an [[Orbital bombardment/Legends|orbital bombardment]] to flush the smugglers out.

After a while, Barris reported in that the signature was from a small encampment, probably from a shipwreck, and definitely from unknown origin, as the team's [[Protocol droid/Legends|3-PO droid]] was unable to identify the markings on the more technologically advanced items. Parck started to order him to settle down for the local night, but they were interrupted by [[Lieutenant/Legends|Lieutenant]] [[Kraven]], who demanded his colonel's presence at one of the downed TIEs' crash site.

Once arrived, Barris saw that the pilot's body had disappeared, and that his flight suit had been stuffed with grasses and berries. More importantly, his survival pack, along with his blaster and grenades had been taken away as well. Believing this to be the work of savage [[Alien/Legends|natives]], Barris ordered his second-in-command, [[Major/Legends|Major]] [[Wyan/Legends|Wyan]], to set up a secure perimeter and to call down reinforcements from the ''Strikefast'', while he had the flight suit and its bizarre content returned to camp for further examination.

A short time later, while Barris and Wyan perplexed over the content of the flight suit, a sudden explosion stirred up the encampment. As both officers spurred into action, trying to determine who or what was attacking them, a second explosion destroyed the tent they just exited, still without any sign of attackers. Wyan theorized that these explosions came from an overloaded [[Power cell/Legends|power pack]], and that the whole show with the flight suit was a feint from the smugglers. Barris agreed and reported in to Parck, who immediately launched TIE fighters to scan the area.

However, as soon as their search began, one of the TIE fighters crashed. Rushing there, Barris and his men found the pilot's body, but again lacking his survival gear, blaster and grenades. Barris immediately conferred with Parck, wondering at their opponent's tactics, until Parck suggested checking if the built-in [[Comlink/Legends|comlinks]] were still in both dead pilots' flight suits. Soon enough, they concluded that one was missing, and Parck had that comlink's frequency shut off. He then ordered Barris and his team to stand down for the night, and to wait for the light hours to continue their investigation.

It would not be an easy night, however: three sentries died at the hands of the invisible attackers, and two more shot each other, believing they had found an intruder. By dawn, a sleep-deprived and very angry Barris suggested conducting an orbital bombardment in spite of standing orders. Parck ordered him to calm down, and to conduct his analysis while he sent down [[Stormtrooper/Legends|stormtroopers]] to secure the site and flush out their enemies.

Suddenly, as they proceeded, all comlinks emitted bursts of static, making communications impossible. Fearing yet another assault, and fed up with wasting the lives of his men, Barris ordered forcefully embarking the whole encampment into the landing crafts, and returning to the ''Strikefast''. At the same time, reports came in from the stormtroopers that one of them was missing.

Barris' team complied, and before embarking, the colonel turned to one of the stormtroopers to announce they were leaving. To his horror, the trooper was then utterly annihilated by yet another explosion, leaving only small bits of his armor behind. Barris then ordered taking off ASAP, fearing an all-out assault. However, they made it back to the ''Strikefast'' without further incident.

Once aboard, a dejected Barris faced Parck, defending his decision of leaving, and expecting a serious reprimand. Parck merely ordered that the docking bay be deserted and bade Barris to follow him to the bay control tower. There they waited in darkness for a few hours until a lone figure emerged hesitantly from the transports. Parck then ordered a squad of stormtroopers to take the intruder into custody.

Moments later, the intruder, actually Thrawn, was brought before both officers. There he explained his exile, his desire to continue defending his people no matter what, and his strategy to force down stormtroopers, so he could steal one of their armors and sneak on the spaceships. Impressed by his resourcefulness, Parck proposed to Thrawn to be brought before [[Palpatine/Legends|the Emperor]], to whom he could be a valuable asset, and from whom he could get the means to defend [[Chiss/Legends|his people]]. Barris scoffed at the idea, saying the Emperor would never employ an alien, which prompted Parck to give his word that he would release Thrawn wherever he wanted to go in case the Emperor refused. Thrawn agreed, and Parck ordered his ship back to [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]] immediately, much to the surprise of Booster Terrik.

==Continuity==
Published in [[1995]], for years ''Mist Encounter'' served as the earliest origin story for [[Grand Admiral/Legends|Grand Admiral]] [[Mitth'raw'nuruodo/Legends|Thrawn]], though it still did not reveal who [[Chiss/Legends|his people]] were and what specific circumstances led to his exile – some of what would wait until [[Outbound Flight (novel)|''Outbound Flight'']] ([[2006]]). [[Timothy Zahn]] wrote ''Mist Encounter'' well before any details of [[Prequel trilogy|Episodes I, II and III]] were shared with [[Star Wars Legends|Expanded Universe]] authors, and though it aligned fairly well with modern continuity, there was a conspicuous absence of any mentions of the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]]. The original short story included a mention of “President Palpatine”, which was changed to [[Supreme Chancellor/Legends|Chancellor]] [[Palpatine/Legends|Palpatine]] when it was reprinted in the ''Outbound Flight'' paperback in [[2007]]. By virtue of its chronology, this story inadvertently marked the debut of the [[TIE series/Legends|TIE]] [[Starfighter/Legends|fighter]]. It also marked the first chronological appearance of [[Booster Terrik]], who would figure prominently in the [[Star Wars: X-Wing (novel series)|X-Wing novels]] and beyond.<ref name="TERC" />

==Legacy==
After [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney's]] acquisition of [[Lucasfilm]] in [[2012]], the Expanded Universe was rebranded into [[Star Wars Legends|"Legends"]] in [[2014]], with both "Mist Encounter" and Thrawn deemed no longer canon along with the rest of the continuity.<ref name="LegendsAnnouncement">{{SW|url=news/the-legendary-star-wars-expanded-universe-turns-a-new-page|text=The Legendary Star Wars Expanded Universe Turns a New Page}}</ref> In [[2016]], however, [[Mitth'raw'nuruodo|Thrawn]] was made canon once again,<ref name="SWR">''[[Star Wars Rebels: Steps Into Shadow]]''</ref> and a [[2017|year later]] Zahn wrote a [[Thrawn (novel)|book about him]]. The first two chapters of the book are almost an exact retelling of "Mist Encounter," down to each individual character, with only a few alterations, such as the incorporation of the point-of-view character [[Eli N. Vanto|Eli Vanto]] and the changing of the ''Strikefast'' from a [[Victory-class Star Destroyer/Legends|''Victory''-class Star Destroyer]] to a [[Venator-class Star Destroyer|''Venator''-class Star Destroyer]].<ref name="ThrawnNovel">[[Thrawn (novel)|''Thrawn'']]</ref> In [[2018]], the novel was adapted into a [[Star Wars: Thrawn (comic series)|comic]]; the [[Thrawn 1|first issue]] adapted the sections of the novel corresponding to "Mist Encounter," with artist [[Luke Ross]] basing his depictions of Thrawn and Parck on Doug Shuler's illustrations of them from the original 1995 short story.

